english:
  title: Preface to the Departure of Song Do-gwan, Inspector of Gyeongsang Province
  author: Lee Saeuk
  language: eng
  text: |-
    Those who nurture the people must be men of worth and measure—how much more so when the court sends forth envoys to inspect the four corners of the realm. Such a man holds the fate of the people in his hands. Through his investigations, the virtues and vices of custom are revealed and corrected; the merit and failing of local governors are discerned and rewarded or punished. Thus does he hold the very instruments of punishment and reward. How can the court entrust such power to one unworthy of it, even for a single day?

    Our realm extends through eight provinces beyond the capital, with prefectures, states, and counties arrayed like stones upon a go board. Each spring and autumn, eight court officials are selected and dispatched to oversee them. Should a man seek renown, the people will suffer. Should he possess generosity and wisdom, they will receive his blessing. The court understands this well and thus takes great care in this selection. Few unworthy of the office have ever been chosen.

    In my years serving in the upper councils, I have participated more than once in these deliberations. Song Do-gwan has always been among the most deserving candidates. Yet he was passed over—being kinsman to Minister Tae-jae, appearance demanded he be set aside to avoid suspicion. But nominations for him grew numerous, and the weight of opinion could not be resisted. Merit cannot forever yield to circumspection.

    Song Do-gwan is a man of integrity and thoughtful bearing, with special gift for administration. Gyeongsang Province, ancient Silla in its entirety, flows with accumulated grace of mountain and stream, preserving still the noble customs of old. Though the land is vast and its affairs many, when governed by a capable hand, all prospers—no other province surpasses it. That such a man should finally be sent to such a place brings me profound joy. As a great fish requires a great river, and a skilled craftsman's talent would be wasted on inferior cloth, so too are this man and this province made for one another. Not only I rejoice at this—all the gentlemen of the court celebrate it. Songs accompany his departure, flowing without end. That he asked me to write this preface, though we have never met face to face, speaks to the esteem he holds. My colleague Kim Baek-eun brought his intention to me.
  footnotes:
  - key: ''
    value: The 'eight provinces' (팔도) refer to the administrative divisions of Goryeo during this period, with inspection officials sent to oversee regional governance and report to the central court.
  - key: ''
    value: Tae-jae (태재) was a high-ranking minister, and Song Do-gwan's kinship relation created a conflict of interest that prevented his appointment despite his qualifications—a demonstration of institutional integrity even at cost to worthy individuals.
  - key: ''
    value: Gyeongsang Province was the territory of ancient Silla, and Lee Saeuk emphasizes its historical cultural preservation as evidence of its particular suitability for capable administration.
